The rain did not stop for Goodman Morell's funeral. Distant thunder rolled through the village. The cemetery hill stood between the village on one side and dense forest on the other. The Vicar stood over the grave Rafe and Matthis had finished together. Mercy stood beside him. Miners and craftsmen stood in a circle around the hilltop. Rafe and Matthis stood on either side of the grave. Goodman Morell's coffin sat at Matthis' feet, thick ropes slung underneath it.

Matthis looked in the direction of the gallows. He could still feel the wizard down there, watching. He felt something prickle on his neck. It wasn't a hand or even the cold. He turned. On the forest side of the hill, a face like an owl peered through the trees. He blinked. The face smiled at him. As he watched, the face vanished into the leaves. When he turned back to the funeral, Mercy was glowering at him. 

The mud squished under every foot. Miners shifted their weight as the Vicar spoke. The pile of turned soil smelled old and stiff in the rain. Rafe leaned on his shovel. He winked when he noticed Matthis looking at him. Mercy's eyes narrowed at the exchange. Rain dripped into the open grave. 

The Vicar finished his speech and nodded at Matthis and Rafe. Matthis and a son of Goodman Morell beside him tossed ropes across the grave. Rafe and another of Goodman Morell's sons caught them. Together, they lowered the coffin into the hole. Goodman Morell's sons held a handful of soil over the coffin. One after the other, they released the soil. It thudded onto the coffin in wet clumps. Several people tossed flowers. For several minutes, no one spoke. No one moved.

Rafe and Matthis nodded. Matthis lifted his shovel. Together, he and Rafe filled the grave. The mud weighed the shovel down and landed on the coffin with a splatter. People looked away from him when he noticed them. 

People slowly drained from the cemetery hill. Rafe and Matthis tamped down the wet soil. Their shovels gonged when they hit rocks. They leaned on their shovels. Mist rose from their mouths. Rafe lifted his shovel and waved at Matthis. He waved back.

Matthis watched Rafe walk down the hill. He turned to the forest side of the hill. Through the haze of rain, he couldn't see anything unusual. He stuck his shovel into the ground with a squelch. He hiked down the hill toward the tree line.

When he reached the spot where the face had been, Matthis looked up. He couldn't see the clouds through the canopy. Water dripped down the leaves. He peered into the forest. He saw bark the shape of a human hand in a nearby tree. It appeared to be grown into the bark. He hesitated at first, then reached out a hand.

"I'm afraid this one caught us."

Matthis froze. Starting at the hand shape, an arm, then a shoulder, then an angular, owl-shaped head bloomed into existence. He couldn't tell whether it was a man or a woman. Leaf patterns covered its skin, or perhaps it wore leaves as clothing. Matthis' head reached the slender being's chest. Matthis backed away. Two more beings stepped forward from nowhere. They had short, hooked noses. Their faces were white and flat. Their eyes were completely black. They did not blink. Matthis stopped breathing.

Their voices sounded like snakes slithering through wet leaves. 

"How curious," said the middle one. "It is afraid."

"Does it wish to dominate us as well?" said the left one.

"What is this?" said the middle one. It reached forward and slipped the black book from Matthis' bag before he could react.

"How long has the incubus dominated this human village?" said the one on the right.

The middle one leafed through the black book. 

"Will you say nothing, Incubus?" said the left one. 

Matthis swallowed. He considered running. But they would catch him. He swallowed again. They still had not blinked.

"Incubus?" he said.

"It makes a jest," said the one holding the book. 

"Will it dominate us?" said the left one.

"It smells of death," said the one on the right, "and mud. And Ever-Death."

The one in the middle pointed to a page on the book. "This Faceless One. It is much like stories of the Old Walker."

They spoke too quickly for Matthis to react. He forced words into their rapid speech.

"I'm not dominating anyone."

They paused. Their bodies relaxed. Their black eyes still hadn't blinked.

"Is the Incubus friendly to us Wood Elves?"

"An Incubus who does not dominate?"

"He is a polite Incubus."

"Will he remain this way forever?"

"We should be friendly to the Incubus before we leave."

"Will the Incubus remain polite to the elves who live nearby?"

"He is a clever Incubus."

"-- My name is Matthis --"

"The Incubus shares his name."

"What a friendly incubus."

"Shame we will never meet him again."

"We are glad for a friendly incubus."

A hand slipped the book back into Matthis' satchel in a blur of motion.

"He is still a young Incubus."

"Goodbye, Incubus Matthis."

"Farewell. Remain kinder to us Wood Elves than the others of your kind."

Matthis blinked. They were gone. 

The place where he had seen a hand in the bark was just normal tree bark. He touched the spot. He hadn't ever heard their footsteps.

The leaves chorused with raindrops overhead. Low rumbles swept through the valley. Matthis turned and hiked up the hill. His shovel was still stuck in the mud. When he looked back, he saw only trees.